Cyclistic Bike-Share Case Study

Your Name

1. Business Task

Cyclistic is a bike-share program in Chicago. The marketing team is interested in understanding how casual riders and annual members use the service differently, with the goal of converting more casual riders into annual members. This case study explores usage patterns using 2019 data.

Merging datasets and selecting relevant columns

trips2019 <- bind_rows(trips_q1, trips_q2v2, trips_q3, trips_q4) %>%
  select(-gender, -birthyear)

Creating derived variables

trips2019 <- trips2019 %>%
  mutate(
    year = year(start_time),
    month = month(start_time, label = TRUE),
    ride_length = tripduration / 60
  ) %>%
  select(-end_time, -start_time, -tripduration)

5. Data Analysis

Ride Duration and Frequency

ride_frequency <- trips_2019v2 %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  summarise(
    average_duration = mean(ride_length),
    median_duration = median(ride_length),
    min_duration = min(ride_length),
    max_duration = max(ride_length)
  )

write_csv(ride_frequency, "Ride_Frequency.csv")
ride_frequency

Monthly Ride Counts

trips_2019v2 <- trips_2019v2 %>%
  mutate(month = factor(month, levels = month.abb, ordered = TRUE))

ride_volume <- trips_2019v2 %>%
  count(usertype, month)

write_csv(ride_volume, "ride_volume.csv")

ggplot(ride_volume, aes(x = month, y = n, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Monthly Ride Counts by User Type", x = "Month", y = "Number of Rides") +
  theme_minimal()

Popular Stations

most_popular_start_station <- trips_2019v2 %>%
  count(usertype, from_station_name, sort = TRUE) %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  slice_max(n, n=5)

write_csv(most_popular_start_station, "most_popular_station.csv")

most_popular_end_station <- trips_2019v2 %>%
  count(usertype, to_station_name) %>%
  group_by(usertype) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 5)

write_csv(most_popular_end_station, "most_popular_end_station.csv")

Visualizing Top Stations

ggplot(most_popular_start_station, aes(x = reorder(from_station_name, n), y = n, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Top 5 Start Stations by User Type",
    x = "Start Station",
    y = "Number of Rides"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

ggplot(most_popular_end_station, aes(x = reorder(to_station_name, n), y = n, fill = usertype)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    title = "Top 5 End Stations by User Type",
    x = "End Station",
    y = "Number of Rides"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

6. Key Insights

  • Casual riders are highly seasonal, peaking in summer and dropping significantly in winter.
  • Annual members ride consistently throughout the year and tend to take shorter trips.
  • Start and end stations vary, indicating different use cases (leisure vs commuting).

7. Recommendations

  • Market to casual users with promotions during warmer months.
  • Incentivize conversions to annual memberships.
  • Improve access or promotions at tourist-heavy start stations.
